revision.text:
[[File:Belfast City & District Water Commissioners, 3% redeemable stock, 1895.jpg|thumb|Belfast City & District Water Commissioners, 3% redeemable stock, 1895.]] [[File:The Mourne Wall, Slievenaglogh - geograph.org.uk - 1773763.jpg|thumb|The Mourne Wall, Slievenaglogh, 2010.]] The '''Belfast City and District Water Commissioners''' was a public body in northern Ireland, established by the [[Belfast Water Act 1840]], to improve the supply of water to the expanding city of Belfast. By 1852, the city was suffering a shortfall in supply of almost one million gallons per day.<ref>[http://www.earc.org.uk/ShortHistoryofBelfastWaterSupply.htm Short History of Belfast’s Mourne Water Supply.] William R Darby, EARC, 2 November 2010. Retrieved 29 January 2018.</ref><ref>[http://www.newulsterbiography.co.uk/index.php/home/viewPerson/929 Luke Livingstone Macassey (1843 - 1908).] Patrick Devlin, Dictionary of Ulster Biography. Retrieved 29 January 2018.</ref>
The commissioners were responsible from 1914 for the construction of the [[Mourne Wall]] which [[Northern Ireland Water]] began to restore in 2017.<ref>[https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/113-years-on-work-begins-to-repair-the-wonder-wall-of-the-mournes-35734916.html 113 years on, work begins to repair the wonder wall of the Mournes.] Allan Preston, ''Belfast Telegraph'', 20 May 2017. Retrieved 29 January 2018.</ref>
Before the Second World War the commissioners purchased a building that is still known as the [[Water Office, Belfast|Water Office]].<ref>[http://www.culturenorthernireland.org/features/heritage/water-office The Water Office.] Culture Northern Ireland. Retrieved 29 January 2018.</ref><ref>[https://apps.communities-ni.gov.uk/Buildings/buildview.aspx?id=17180&js=false HB26/50/015.] Department for Communities. Retrieved 29 January 2018.</ref><ref>[http://www.victorianweb.org/art/architecture/misc/34.html Richardson & Owden's Warehouse.] Victorian Web, 13 September 2006. Retrieved 29 January 2018.</ref>
In the later twentieth century, responsibility for providing water services was transferred to central government in Northern Ireland and, eventually, to Northern Ireland Water.
