The '''European Environmental Press (EEP)''' is a [[Europe]]-wide association of nearly two dozen environmental magazines.<ref>[http://water.environmental-expert.com/STSE_ResultEach.aspx?cid=6725&idproducttype=1&level=0 EEP European Environmental Press] from [http://www.environmental-expert.com/index.aspx Environmental Expert website]. Retrieved April 2009.</ref> The combined circulation is 800.000. Each member is considered the leader in its country and is committed to building links between 400,000 environmental professionals across Europe in both the [[public sector|public]] and [[private sector]]s. The EEP is unique in bringing together the leading national [[business-to-business]] magazines as an expert network for the dissemination of high-quality environmental information throughout Europe. The target market for EEP is highly educated individuals. It deals with different environmental issues across the board, including water supply, waste management, recycling,remediation of contaminated land, air pollution, noise, energy, and tracking technologies as well as environmental administration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vanha.uusiouutiset.fi/eep.htm|title=EEP|last=|first=|date=|website=Uusiouutiset|publisher=|access-date=November 15, 2016}}</ref> The magazine is highly technologically optimistic and has focused on many technological solutions to environmental problems.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Transnational Identity Politics and the Environment|last=Ignatow|first=Gabriel|publisher=Lexington Books|year=2007|isbn=|location=Lanham|pages=66|quote=|via=}}</ref>
The European Environmental Press presents various companies with awards that relate to creating clever and efficient solutions to environmental problems as well as in their efforts to reduce pollution and contribute to bettering the environment.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Transnational Identity Politics and the Environment|last=Gabriel|first=Ignatow|publisher=Lexington Books|year=2007|isbn=|location=Lanham|pages=67|quote=|via=Google Books}}</ref> They do this in association with Pollutec,a French trade-show company and is endorsed by The European Network of Environmental Professionals (EFAP). Applications are announced and nobody is exempt from the opportunity to participate.A committee gathers and nominates ten winners from all the ones that applied. The committee then decides the winners from the nominated batch. There are three winners, gold, silver and bronze. The gold winners receive spreads in the EEP magazines and they also get the opportunity to present their projects at various conferences across Europe the most important one being Pollutec. Being nominated is also useful for the companies as their work often gets cited in the magazine, sparking discussion, fundraising and inspiration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cleanlaser.de/wEnglish/news/meldungen/2009-10-14-51996617-meldung.php?navanchor=2110061|title=Nominated for EEP Award 2009|last=|first=|date=|website=Clean Laser|publisher=Clean Laser|access-date=November 15, 2016}}</ref> {| class="sortable" |+'''Examples of Companies and Countries Winning the EEP Award''' !Company !Country !Year |- |Lenzing Group |Austria |2011 |- |Oilguard |Switzerland |2011 |- |Nonox |Denmark |2009 |- |Nanovis |Switzerland |2007 |- |Yara |Norway |2007 |- |Umicore Batteries |Belgium and Germany |2004 |- |Interline Resources Corp |Spain and USA |2004 |}
