'''Japan Photovoltaic Energy Association''' (JPEA) is the best-known body for [[solar energy|solar]] [[Photovoltaics|photovoltaic]] energy companies in Japan. Founded on April 23, 1987, it has a number of objectives and activities, one of which is providing the JPEC certification for [[solar module]]s in the Japanese market. The association serves as a spokesperson for the [[photovoltaics industry|photovoltaics energy industry]] in Japan.

JPEA set a pathway for the photovoltaic industry in Japan to reach 100 [[gigawatt|GW]] by 2030, from roughly 30 GW in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cleantechnica.com/2016/03/10/fossil-fuels-lose-japans-power-sector-transformation/|title=Fossil Fuels Lose Out In Japan’s Power Sector Transformation|website=CleanTechnica|access-date=2016-03-29}}</ref> The group comprises multiple companies in the industry, and reported a 13% drop in total [[photovoltaic solar panel]] shipments in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.solarplaza.com/channels/markets/11473/japan-market-shift-looks-good-larger-projects/|title=Solarplaza Japan market shift looks good for larger projects|website=www.solarplaza.com|access-date=2016-03-29}}</ref>

